I've found the JavaScript code that handles session deletion in the Moltis web UI. Here's the complete flow:

### 1. Delete Button Click Handler
**File:** `/Users/penso/tmp/molt/moltis/crates/web/src/assets/js/components/session-header.js` (lines 196-227)

The delete button triggers the `onDelete` callback:
```javascript
var onDelete = useCallback(() => {
    if (typeof onBeforeDelete === "function") {
        onBeforeDelete();
    }
    var currentSession = sessionStore.getByKey(currentKey);
    var msgCount = currentSession ? currentSession.messageCount || 0 : 0;
    var nextKey = nextSessionKey(currentKey);
    var doDelete = () => {
        sendRpc("sessions.delete", { key: currentKey }).then((res) => {
            if (res && !res.ok && res.error && res.error.indexOf("uncommitted changes") !== -1) {
                confirmDialog("Worktree has uncommitted changes. Force delete?").then((yes) => {
                    if (!yes) return;
                    sendRpc("sessions.delete", { key: currentKey, force: true }).then(() => {
                        switchSession(nextKey);
                        fetchSessions();
                    });
                });
                return;
            }
            switchSession(nextKey);
            fetchSessions();
        });
    };
    var isUnmodifiedFork = currentSession && currentSession.forkPoint != null && msgCount <= currentSession.forkPoint;
    if (msgCount > 0 && !isUnmodifiedFork) {
        confirmDialog("Delete this session?").then((yes) => {
            if (yes) doDelete();
        });
    } else {
        doDelete();
    }
}, [currentKey, onBeforeDelete, sessionDataVersion]);
```

The Delete button is rendered in the SessionHeader (lines 494-506):
```javascript
${
    showDelete &&
    !isMain &&
    html`
    <button
        class=${`${actionButtonClass} chat-session-btn-danger inline-flex items-center gap-1.5`}
        onClick=${onDelete}
        title="Delete session"
        style=${{ background: "var(--error)", borderColor: "var(--error)", color: "#fff" }}
    >
        <span class="icon icon-sm icon-x-circle shrink-0"></span>
        Delete
    </button>
`
}
```

### 2. RPC Call & Confirmation Modal
**File:** `/Users/penso/tmp/molt/moltis/crates/web/src/assets/js/ui.js` (lines 111-157)

The `confirmDialog()` function creates a modal with:
- A message prompt
- Cancel button (secondary style)
- Delete button (danger style, red)
- The Delete button resolves the promise with `true`, Cancel resolves with `false`

The RPC call is made via `sendRpc("sessions.delete", { key: currentKey })` or `sendRpc("sessions.delete", { key: currentKey, force: true })` if there are uncommitted changes in a worktree.

### 3. DOM Removal After Deletion
**File:** `/Users/penso/tmp/molt/moltis/crates/web/src/assets/js/app.js` (lines 126-141)

The `removeSessionFromEvent()` function handles DOM removal:
1. Calls `sessionStore.remove(sessionKey)` which filters out the session from the reactive signal
2. Updates the legacy state: `S.setSessions(S.sessions.filter((session) => session.key !== sessionKey))`
3. Calls `renderSessionList()` to trigger re-render of the session list component
4. Clears session history cache: `clearSessionHistoryCache(sessionKey)`
5. If the deleted session was active, it switches to the next session

### 4. WebSocket Event Handling
**File:** `/Users/penso/tmp/molt/moltis/crates/web/src/assets/js/app.js` (lines 143-155)

The WebSocket event listener handles server-sent deletion notifications:
```javascript
onEvent("session", (payload) => {
    if (!payload?.kind) return;
    if (payload.kind === "deleted") {
        if (!removeSessionFromEvent(payload.sessionKey)) {
            fetchSessions();
        }
        return;
    }
    // ... handle other event types
});
```

When a `"deleted"` event is received with a `sessionKey`, it calls `removeSessionFromEvent()` which removes the session from the reactive store and re-renders the session list.

### Session Store Remove Implementation
**File:** `/Users/penso/tmp/molt/moltis/crates/web/src/assets/js/stores/session-store.js` (lines 210-221)

The `remove()` function:
1. Filters the session from the reactive `sessions` signal
2. Updates the active session key if the deleted session was active (falls back to "main" or the first available session)
3. Persists the new active session key to localStorage

This ensures automatic re-render via Preact signal subscription and proper navigation away from deleted sessions.

